publications.name: Owl-Eye: An AI-Driven Visual Testing Tool
publications.description: Visual testing is a software testing technique that checks the visual aspects of a Graphical User Interface (GUI). It helps identify visual defects that other GUI testing techniques, such as functional and performance tests, may not detect. While functional testing verifies the correct behavior of applications, it is not effective in catching visual issues. This paper introduces an AI-driven visual tester, a novel approach to visual testing that enhances the detection of visual defects in application interfaces. The tester can effectively test any platform, using screenshots as input. The process begins with object detection in the screenshots, employing two methods: traditional image processing and deep learning. The detected objects are then transformed into a tree data structure for efficient analysis. Object matching is utilized to correlate objects between the reference and updated images. Finally, change analysis and classification are performed to identify and categorize changes in each object, such as translation, scaling, color change, or object removal

publications.name: Indoor Antenna Placement Automation with Meta-heuristic Optimization
publications.description:
The paper presents a cutting-edge framework called Antenna Placement Simulator and Optimizer (APSO). This innovative tool utilizes meta-heuristic algorithms and MATLAB simulation to optimize antenna placement in indoor environments.

With 5G and other high-frequency wireless technologies on the rise, finding optimal antenna locations is crucial for ensuring reliable coverage. However, the challenges posed by higher frequency bands, such as mmWave, demand sophisticated solutions. APSO addresses these challenges by considering realistic scenarios, including 3D environments and non-line-of-sight conditions, while optimizing for criteria like path loss and received power.

Our framework evaluates the effectiveness of two popular meta-heuristic algorithms, Genetic Algorithm (GA) and Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO), shedding light on their strengths and weaknesses. Additionally, we introduce an adaptive algorithm for dynamic antenna relocation based on receiver positions, showcasing its effectiveness in changing scenarios.
